# Settings UI And Status Bar Refactor Plan

## Goal

Improve the Settings UI and simplify the Status Bar configuration so that:

- the page structure is cleaner and less nested
- provider visibility rules are consistent
- enabled items are always sorted above disabled items
- the pay-as-you-go and subscription concepts for OpenCode / OpenCode Go / Zen are clearly separated
- Status Bar settings reflect the actual product behavior instead of exposing legacy or unused modes

## User Decisions

The following decisions are already approved and must be preserved:

- The Status Bar settings page should focus on a single effective mode, because the app is effectively using only `Multi-Provider`.
- `Enabled Providers` should be visually split into:
  - `Pay-as-you-go`
  - `Subscriptions`
- `Critical Badge` should move to `General`.
- `OpenCode`, `OpenCode Go`, and `Zen` must remain distinct concepts:
  - `OpenCode`: pay-as-you-go usage
  - `OpenCode Go`: Go subscription
  - `Zen`: Zen subscription

## Current Findings

### 1. Status Bar mode is effectively hardcoded to Multi-Provider

The current implementation always returns `.multiProvider` from `StatusBarController.menuBarDisplayMode`.

References:
- `CopilotMonitor/CopilotMonitor/App/StatusBarController.swift:179-187`

Impact:
- The current Settings UI still exposes concepts such as `Only Show`, `Total Cost`, and `Icon Only`, but the active controller path is effectively pinned to Multi-Provider behavior.
- The Settings page should therefore be simplified around the one real mode the app uses.

### 2. Status Bar settings are currently split into multiple overlapping sections

Current `StatusBarSettingsView` sections:
- `Enabled Providers`
- `Additional Cost Items`
- `Multi-Provider Bar Providers`
- `Options`

References:
- `CopilotMonitor/CopilotMonitor/App/Settings/StatusBarSettingsView.swift:7-35`

Impact:
- Provider visibility is controlled in two places:
  - enabled state
  - multi-provider selection
- This creates inconsistent UX because a provider can be disabled in one list while still appearing selected in another list.

### 3. The current code already filters disabled providers in several menu paths, but the settings model is still inconsistent

Examples:
- Pay-as-you-go rows skip disabled providers
- Quota rows skip disabled providers
- Multi-provider status bar rendering also skips disabled providers

References:
- `CopilotMonitor/CopilotMonitor/App/StatusBarController.swift:1343-1348`
- `CopilotMonitor/CopilotMonitor/App/StatusBarController.swift:1561`
- `CopilotMonitor/CopilotMonitor/App/StatusBarController.swift:1709`
- `CopilotMonitor/CopilotMonitor/App/StatusBarController.swift:1861`

Impact:
- Runtime rendering partially respects enabled state.
- Settings UX still allows stale selections to remain inside `multiProviderProviders`, which makes the page feel broken.

### 4. Toggle ordering is currently static, not state-aware

Current provider lists iterate directly over `ProviderIdentifier.allCases`.

References:
- `CopilotMonitor/CopilotMonitor/App/Settings/StatusBarSettingsView.swift:11-13`
- `CopilotMonitor/CopilotMonitor/App/Settings/StatusBarSettingsView.swift:25-27`

Impact:
- After toggling a provider, enabled items do not float to the top.
- The same problem exists conceptually in subscription settings, where rows are assembled by provider enumeration and saved key order rather than by user relevance.

### 5. OpenCode / OpenCode Go / Zen are not modeled clearly enough for the desired UX

Important current facts:

- `ProviderIdentifier` contains both `.openCode` and `.openCodeZen`
- only `OpenCodeZenProvider()` is currently registered in `ProviderManager`
- pay-as-you-go menu order is hardcoded to `[.openRouter, .openCodeZen]`
- subscription presets for both `openCode` and `openCodeZen` are empty

References:
- `CopilotMonitor/CopilotMonitor/Models/ProviderProtocol.swift:12-59`
- `CopilotMonitor/CopilotMonitor/Services/ProviderManager.swift:28-43`
- `CopilotMonitor/CopilotMonitor/App/StatusBarController.swift:1559`
- `CopilotMonitor/CopilotMonitor/Models/SubscriptionSettings.swift:167-169`

Impact:
- The app currently exposes `OpenCode Zen` as the pay-as-you-go item because that is the only registered provider supplying this data.
- The current subscription settings model does not yet express the separate subscription products implied by `OpenCode Go` and `Zen`.

## Refactor Targets

## A. Status Bar Settings Page

### Target structure

Replace the current four-section layout with a single coherent page made of:

- `Pay-as-you-go`
- `Subscriptions`

Move the following out of this page:

- `Critical Badge` -> `General`

Remove or hide from this page:

- the separate `Multi-Provider Bar Providers` section
- the separate `Additional Cost Items` section as a standalone concept
- legacy mode-oriented UI that implies multiple active status bar display modes

### Behavior rules

For each provider row on the Status Bar page:

- one toggle controls whether the provider is eligible to appear in the status bar
- turning a provider off must also remove it from `multiProviderProviders`
- turning a provider on should add it back to `multiProviderProviders` by default
- enabled items sort above disabled items
- stable provider order is preserved inside each enabled/disabled group

### Grouping rules

`Pay-as-you-go`
- OpenRouter
- OpenCode
- GitHub Copilot Add-on if it remains user-toggleable

`Subscriptions`
- GitHub Copilot
- Claude
- Kimi for Coding
- MiniMax Coding Plan
- ChatGPT
- Z.AI Coding Plan
- Nano-GPT
- Antigravity
- Chutes AI
- Synthetic
- Gemini CLI
- future OpenCode Go / Zen subscription rows if and when they are modeled as subscribable products

## B. General Settings Page

Move `Critical Badge` into `GeneralSettingsView`.

References:
- `CopilotMonitor/CopilotMonitor/App/Settings/GeneralSettingsView.swift:10-68`
- `CopilotMonitor/CopilotMonitor/App/Settings/AppPreferences.swift:80-85`

Expected result:
- Status Bar page becomes focused on provider visibility only.
- General page contains global display behavior toggles.

## C. Subscription Settings Page

### UI goal

Reduce the current button-heavy layout and make it cleaner and less nested.

Current issues:
- each row uses many plain bordered buttons
- rows feel visually noisy
- the selection model looks cheap and crowded

References:
- `CopilotMonitor/CopilotMonitor/App/Settings/SubscriptionSettingsView.swift:168-273`

### Target interaction

Each row should become simpler:

- provider name on the left
- current monthly cost summary on the right
- a compact preset selector instead of many equal-weight bordered buttons
- custom amount input only appears when needed

### Sorting rules

Rows should sort by relevance:

- enabled providers first
- disabled providers after that
- orphaned saved subscription keys at the bottom

Within each block:
- use a stable business order, not random key order

## D. OpenCode / OpenCode Go / Zen Modeling Cleanup

This is the most important logic clarification area.

### Desired product distinction

- `OpenCode`: pay-as-you-go usage item
- `OpenCode Go`: subscription product
- `Zen`: subscription product

### Current mismatch

The codebase currently uses `OpenCodeZenProvider` as the pay-as-you-go data source and surfaces `OpenCode Zen` in the pay-as-you-go UI.

This is likely wrong for the desired product model.

### Planned resolution

Phase 1:
- do not rename blindly at the UI layer
- first map which provider/result object actually represents:
  - OpenCode pay-as-you-go
  - OpenCode Go subscription
  - Zen subscription

Phase 2:
- update user-facing labels only after the provider-to-product mapping is correct
- ensure pay-as-you-go shows `OpenCode` only if the underlying data truly represents OpenCode pay-as-you-go
- ensure subscription settings gain explicit modeling for `OpenCode Go` and `Zen` if they are real subscribable products

### Required code areas to inspect during implementation

- `CopilotMonitor/CopilotMonitor/Providers/OpenCodeZenProvider.swift`
- `CopilotMonitor/CopilotMonitor/Services/ProviderManager.swift`
- `CopilotMonitor/CopilotMonitor/Models/ProviderProtocol.swift`
- `CopilotMonitor/CopilotMonitor/Models/SubscriptionSettings.swift`
- `CopilotMonitor/CopilotMonitor/App/StatusBarController.swift`

